To ensure better sensitivity, we optimized incubation time. The kinetic curve in Fig. S5 shows that the response of CuNCs-CCM to ClO- can reach a constant value of F436/F536 in 3 min. Thus, 3 min was chosen as the optimal reaction time for subsequent research. As shown in Fig. 5
                        a, with the increase of ClO- concentration, the CCM fluorescence at 536 nm decreased whereas the CuNCs fluorescence at 436 nm increased. By plotting the F436/F536 values against ClO- concentration (Fig. 5b), two good linear relationship can be obtained in the range of 0–0.73 µM (Fig. 5c) and 0.73–412 µM (Fig. 5d). The regression equation can be described as: F = 0.20587C + 0.28314 (R2 = 0.992), F = 0.00317C + 0.42951 (R2 = 0.996), with the limit of detection of 24 nM (S/N = 3). Compared with other methods for ClO- detection, this method showed a lower detection limit and a wider detection range (Table 1
                        ). Moreover, after adding ClO-, an obvious mixture color change (from yellow to colorless) and fluorescent color change (from yellow to blue) in the Cu NCs-CCM dispersions can also be observed (Fig. 5e), implying the potential of Cu NCs- as a naked visual probe for the semiquantitative analysis of ClO-.
